│ are candidates for horizontal reduction.                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The assertion `(Idx + EltsPerVector) <= BaseVF` ensures that the subvector extraction is within the bounds of the source vector.                                                         │
│ - `Idx`: Start index of the extraction.                                                                                                                                                  │
│ - `EltsPerVector`: Size of the subvector being extracted.                                                                                                                                │
│ - `BaseVF`: Size of the source vector.                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The crash implies that `Idx + EltsPerVector` is greater than `BaseVF`.                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Looking at the code around the assertion in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`:                                                                                           │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ // In ShuffleCostEstimator::computeExtractCost                                                                                                                                           │
│ case TTI::SK_ExtractSubvector: {                                                                                                                                                         │
│   unsigned EltsPerVector = PowerOf2Ceil(Mask.size());                                                                                                                                    │
│   unsigned Idx = I * EltsPerVector;                                                                                                                                                      │
│   assert((Idx + EltsPerVector) <= BaseVF &&                                                                                                                                              │
│          "SK_ExtractSubvector index out of range");                                                                                                                                      │
│   Cost += TTI.getShuffleCost(*Kinds[I],                                                                                                                                                  │
│                              VectorType::get(VL[0]->getType(), BaseVF),                                                                                                                  │
│                              Idx, nullptr);                                                                                                                                              │
│   break;                                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ }                                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ Here, `EltsPerVector` is calculated as `PowerOf2Ceil(Mask.size())`. `Mask.size()` is the number of elements being extracted in the current group. `I` is the group index.                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The stack trace shows the call chain `vectorizeHorReduction` -> `getTreeCost` -> `getEntryCost` -> `processBuildVector` -> `adjustExtracts` -> `computeExtractCost`.                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem seems to be that `BaseVF` is too small. `BaseVF` is passed down from `adjustExtracts`. In `adjustExtracts`, `BaseVF` is `TE->getVectorFactor()`. `TE` is a `TreeEntry`.      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `TreeEntry` for a horizontal reduction has a vectorization factor that is a power of 2, determined by `PowerOf2Ceil(NumScalars)`. However, the operands of the reduction might be    │
│ vectorized with a different, non-power-of-2 vector factor if `-slp-vectorize-non-power-of-2` is enabled.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The reproducer uses `-slp-vectorize-non-power-of-2`. The reduction chain has 4 inputs, so `NumScalars` is 4, and the reduction's `VF` will be 4. The operands, however, might be part of │
│ a larger group of scalars being vectorized together, for example, a group of 6. If so, their `VF` would be 6.                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ When `adjustExtracts` is called for the reduction's operands, it's trying to extract a subvector of size 4 (the reduction size) from a vector of size 6. The `BaseVF` passed to          │
│ `computeExtractCost` would be the `VF` of the reduction node, which is 4. But the extraction is happening from a vector of size 6. The logic in `adjustExtracts` seems to incorrectly    │
│ use the reduction's `VF` instead of the operand's `VF`.                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The fix is to use the correct vector factor for the base vector. In `adjustExtracts`, when we are processing the operands of a reduction, the base vector is the vectorized operand. Its │
│ vector factor can be found by looking up the `TreeEntry` for that operand.                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `adjustExtracts` function takes a `TreeEntry` `TE`. If `TE` represents a horizontal reduction, it iterates through its operands. For each operand, it tries to find a `TreeEntry` in │
│ `BoUp.VectorizableTree`. If found, this `OpTE` will have the correct vector factor for the operand's vector. This `OpTE->getVectorFactor()` should be used as `BaseVF`. If no            │
│ `TreeEntry` is found for the operand, it means the operand is a scalar, and we should use `TE->getVectorFactor()`.                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will apply a patch that implements this logic. It modifies `adjustExtracts` to correctly determine `BaseVF` when dealing with operands of a horizontal reduction.                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
